{
  "doc_id": "1717",
  "text": "Weeds are mainly controlled manually, mechanically or chemically. The first option, hand weeding, is labor intensive; in upland rice systems hand weeding was estimated to take 173 to 376 person-hours per hectare, depending on the number of weeding interventions [CITATION_1] . Mechanical tools for weeding, either person-driven, animaldriven or engine-driven, are scarce in rice systems in Africa [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , despite a latent interest from farmers [CITATION_4] . Herbicide application, when applied well, is usually the most effective and least labor-intensive weed control method with the highest yield return . This technology, however, relies heavily on the availability of wellfunctioning agro-chemical supply markets as well as on sufficient financial means and know-how on application techniques at the level of the farmer or service provider. These preconditions are often not met in smallholder rice systems in rural areas in SSA [CITATION_5] . Therefore, adoption rates of herbicides in SSA are estimated to be low [CITATION_6] , and application characteristics i.e. herbicide choice, rate and timing, are assumed to deviate frequently from the recommendations [CITATION_7] ) with potential negative consequences for the environment, human health, crop performance [CITATION_8] ) and hence food security.",
